General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (7) Fail to promptly provide copies of contract documents to the consumer or the
2 consumer's attorney upon request.
3 (8) Provide legal advice to the consumer regarding the consumer legal funding
4 transaction or the underlying legal claim.
5 (9) Report a consumer to a credit reporting agency if insufficient funds remain
6 from the net proceeds to repay the company unless the consumer has
7 committed fraud against the consumer legal funding company.
8 (10) Knowingly provide funding to a consumer who has previously assigned or
9 sold a portion of the consumer's right to proceeds from the consumer's legal
10 claim without first purchasing a prior unsatisfied consumer legal funding
11 company's entire funded amount and contracted charges, unless a lesser
12 amount is otherwise expressly agreed to in writing by the consumer legal
13 funding companies. Multiple consumer legal funding companies, however,
14 may agree to contemporaneously provide funding to a consumer so long as
15 the consumer and the consumer's attorney consent to the agreement in writing.
16 (11) Collect from a consumer any fees or charges not authorized under this Article.
17 (12) Sell a contract in whole or in part to a third party. However, if the consumer
18 legal funding company retains responsibility for collecting payment,
19 administering, and otherwise enforcing the consumer legal funding contract,
20 this prohibition does not apply to any of the following:
21 a. An assignment to a wholly owned subsidiary of the consumer legal
22 funding company.
23 b. An assignment to an affiliate of the consumer legal funding company
24 that is under common control.
25 c. The granting of a security interest under Article 9 of Chapter 25 of the
26 General Statutes or as otherwise permitted by law.
27 "§ 58-94-45. Attorney prohibitions.
28 An attorney retained by a consumer for a legal claim shall not have a financial interest in the
29 consumer legal funding company offering consumer legal funding to the consumer. Additionally,
30 any attorney who has referred the consumer to the consumer's retained attorney shall not have a
31 financial interest in the consumer legal funding company offering consumer legal funding to the
32 consumer. A consumer legal funding contract that violates this section is null and void, and no
33 person has a right to collect, attempt to collect, receive, or retain any funded amount or charges
34 related to the consumer legal funding.
35 "§ 58-94-50. Effect of communication on privileges.
36 Communications between a consumer's attorney and a consumer legal funding company
37 necessary to ascertain the status of a legal claim or a legal claim's expected value shall not be
38 discoverable by a party with whom the claim is filed or against whom the claim is asserted. This
39 section does not limit, waive, or abrogate the scope or nature of any statutory or common-law
40 privilege, including the work-product doctrine and the attorney-client privilege.
41 "§ 58-94-55. Disclosure of consumer legal funding transactions.
42 (a) Within 30 calendar days of receipt of a written request, a consumer shall disclose to
43 any party to a legal claim whether the consumer has entered into a consumer legal funding
44 transaction.
45 (b) If a consumer enters into a consumer legal funding transaction after responding to a
46 request pursuant to subsection (a) of this section, the consumer shall disclose this fact to the
47 requesting person within 30 calendar days after the consumer entered into the transaction.
48 "§ 58-94-60. Discovery and admission of consumer legal funding contracts.
49 (a) Discovery. – Consumer legal funding contracts are presumed to be discoverable in a
50 civil action, notwithstanding any agreement or provision with respect to confidentiality. A
51 consumer may seek to rebut this presumption.
Page 6 House Bill 925-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) Admission. – Consumer legal funding transactions disclosed pursuant to
2 G.S. 58-94-55 and consumer legal funding contracts discovered pursuant to subsection (a) of this
3 section are presumed to be inadmissible as evidence. A party may seek to rebut this presumption.
4 "§ 58-94-65. Examinations; charges.
5 For the purpose of protecting consumer interests and determining a consumer legal funding
6 company's financial stability and compliance with the requirements of this Article, the
7 Commissioner may conduct an examination of a consumer legal funding company. The company
8 shall reimburse the Department of Insurance all reasonable costs and expenses of the
9 examination. In unusual circumstances and in the interests of justice, the Commissioner may
10 waive reimbursement for the costs and expenses of an examination under this section.
11 "§ 58-94-70. Rules.
12 The Commissioner may adopt rules necessary for the proper enforcement of this Article.
13 Before proposing a rule, the Commissioner shall notify all companies registered or pending
14 registration under this Article.
15 "§ 58-94-75. Penalties; enforcement.
16 (a) After notice and an opportunity for hearing, the Commissioner may do any of the
17 following if the Commissioner determines that a consumer legal funding company willfully
18 violated any provision of this Article:
19 (1) Revoke, suspend, or refuse to renew a consumer legal funding company's
20 registration.
21 (2) Order a consumer legal funding company to cease and desist from entering
22 into additional consumer legal funding transactions.
23 (3) Assess a civil penalty of not more than ten thousand dollars ($10,000) for each
24 violation. The clear proceeds of any penalty assessed pursuant to this section
25 shall be remitted to the Civil Penalty and Forfeiture Fund in accordance with
26 G.S. 115C-457.2.
27 (4) Order the consumer legal financing company to make restitution to an injured
28 consumer.
29 (b) The powers vested in the Commissioner by this Article are in addition to and do not
30 limit the ability of the Commissioner or any other officer, employee, or agent of the State to take
31 enforcement action."
32 SECTION 2. If any provision of this act or its application to any person or
33 circumstance is held invalid, the invalidity does not affect other provisions or applications of this
34 act that can be given effect without the invalid provision or application and, to this end, the
35 provisions of this act are severable.
36 SECTION 3. This act becomes effective October 1, 2025.
